Russia and Turkey: an alliance of outsiders?
It was a gesture that put an end to the crisis.
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to shake hands for reconciliation and to formally end an eight-month war of words and economic sanctions.
However, when Vladimir Putin received his Turkish counterpart in the golden hall of his palace in St. Petersburg, I got the clear impression that Ankara had a greater desire for reconciliation.
The two sides shook hands,
But Putin’s smile looked thin, and he didn’t radiate much warmth, even by his own reticent standards.
Recep Tayyip Erdogan, on the other hand, repeatedly spoke about his “good friend” Mr Putin – five times, according to one report.
I myself did not keep count.
In addition, he promised that relations with Russia will return even better than before the crisis.
The next day, a newspaper in our country reported that Erdogan had behaved as if nothing bad had ever happened.
I understood his enthusiasm quite the opposite.
But the constant coolness emanating from Putin showed that the Russian Head of State has not forgotten anything.
In fact, the first thing Putin mentioned in his opening speech was the cause of the crisis: Turkey shot down a Russian fighter jet on the Syrian border.
Moscow’s reaction at the time was furious.
Putin attacked Ankara and accused him of stabbing him in the back.
The insult was all the greater because it came from a supposed friend.
It will be difficult, if not impossible, to regain true trust.
The public opinion of the Russian people has also changed since November.
For months, the state-controlled media campaigned extensively and aggressively against Ankara.
Suddenly it seemed that the Turks were to blame for everything.
Most serious were the allegations by top officials that Erdogan’s own family has profited from illegal oil trade in ISIL-controlled areas of Syria.
Erdogan has strongly denied the accusations.
The official message from Peter, however, was that it was time to move on.
After all, this meeting was arranged only to get the apology that Putin demanded from President Erdogan.
In this way, Russia could gain some kind of victory.
The benefits of declaring a truce are clear.
Above all, Erdogan needs all the friends he can get after he was almost ousted from power last month in a failed coup.
The repeated terrorist attacks in Turkey have clearly shaken him, too.
There is also an economic incentive to the settlement.
Russian sanctions have hit Turkey hard, especially the charter flight ban, as several million Russian tourists normally travel to the Turkish coast each year.
The number has dropped by almost 90%.
As far as Russia is concerned, tour operators and charter companies will certainly breathe a sigh of relief when air travel can finally be resumed.
They put their faith in a late-season rush to the Mediterranean.
And even this week, state television has predicted that the price of fruit and vegetables will fall as Turkish agricultural products are allowed to be imported again.
"You touristed there, tomatoes back here," the article in the financial magazine Vedemosti said.
But the visit also had greater political value for Moscow.
Ankara is angry with the West because it believes that the West has reacted tacitly to the attempted coup.
Not to forget the old grudge against Turkey’s snail-paced EU accession negotiations and Putin’s meddling in the affairs of a Putin who is eager to take advantage of cool relations and break Turkey’s ties with the West.
The Russian leader undoubtedly won bonus points from Ankara when it expressed its support for the elected authorities after the attempted coup.
This was self-evident to Moscow, which has its own preoccupation with the change of power.
Thus, at their summit meeting in a gaudy seaside palace, Russia and Turkey were able to convey what one analyst described as an "alliance of outsiders": two countries that feel abandoned and mistreated by the West joining forces.
Despite public reconciliation, the two continue to have major differences.
The most significant is Syria, where Moscow has created an image of itself as a peace-builder, but where Russia and Turkey support the opposing sides.
It is very telling that, after almost three hours of initial talks, both presidents told the press that they had not addressed the issue at all.
The Turkish President deliberately refused to answer the question of the disagreements between the two countries, while Putin, in turn, stressed them.
There is no clear consensus among the countries on where they could seek consensus in Syria.
In view of the possibility of a complete catastrophe caused by the shooting down of a Russian fighter plane by NATO member Turkey, it is undoubtedly better that, after months of open hostility, the two Heads of State should at least be speaking again.
Royal Bank of Scotland is disappearing from customers outside Scotland
According to the Governor of RBS, the bank's operations outside Scotland will be reduced so that in the future it will only offer business services, i.e. back office services.
The Royal Bank of Scotland is disappearing from its customers outside Scotland.
Ross McEwan told BBC Scotland that the RBS brand was originally linked to the bank’s global ambitions.
The bank was forced to backtrack when it nearly collapsed eight years ago and had to be rescued.
During that time, brand strategists have used RBS to protect other consumer finance brands.
It sponsors international sports for millions of pounds, including Six Nations rugby and Wimbledon champion Andy Murray.
But now it has been considered right to let more national brands come to the fore.
The Royal Bank of Scotland will continue to be used by Scottish customers, but will not be known as RBS.
In England and Wales, all RBS names are changed to NatWest except for headquarters and stock exchange listing.
The Ulster Bank brand is already in use in the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland.
In addition, there are other smaller private banking brands that will gain greater weight, such as Coutts, Adam & Co, Drummond and Holt's Military Bank.
McEwan was interviewed during a customer and staff presentation in Invernessshire.
He told BBC Scotland: “RBS is becoming an investment brand and the one that our staff are employed by because we are now becoming a bank of many more different brands.
As the bank itself became a global brand, RBS also became a global brand.
Now our aspirations are no longer global, but local.
Each of these brands represents something quite different in their own community, and our staff works with customers under these brands.”
RBS has already announced that it will stop sponsoring Six Nations rugby, and it has raised the profile of various brands in sports sponsorship.
“Now is the right time to move to a multi-brand bank, because it’s fundamentally about how we can make the bank better for our customers,” he said.
“It would have been very sarcastic three years ago if we had said that we would be an excellent bank for our customers and introduced brands.
But our work and focus on our customers’ needs instead of our own has changed a lot.
We can bring those brands back, so I think the time is right.”
