Pokémon Go Hunt for Health and Happiness
It is fascinating to see how the world is changing.
Over the past decade, many have complained about why teenagers and children no longer go out to play, preferring to stay inside and stare at their screens.
Pokémon Go gets people off the couch and on the move.
Initially, screen time was limited to watching TV, then video games, and most recently smartphones.
So it’s great to see that technology and outdoor exercise are not mutually exclusive.
Pokémon Go is a game app that features characters from a video game that was created in the 1990s (which later became a series of cartoons, playing cards, and other related products).
Like many popular cultural phenomena, this also ended a bit before the new game became available in the US, Australia and New Zealand in early July.
The launch in other countries was delayed by a huge interest that overloaded the servers.
In just a few days, Pokémon Go surpassed Tinder and was almost as high as Twitter.
How does the game work?
In short, players go out to look for Pokémon on their smartphones, which are tracked by GPS. When a Pokémon is found, it can be "photographed" (using the screen of the phone) or "captured".
The fad has swept away a generation that played video games when they were younger and lifted their butts off the couch.
In the United States, the game has significantly increased the number of steps that the "average" person takes per day.
The Washington Post recently reported, on the Apple Watch smartwatch Cardiogram app, which found within two days of the launch of the game that the number of people moving 30 minutes a day suddenly rose from 45 percent to 53 percent. Cardiogram tracks 35,000 users.
The company doesn’t know which user is playing Pokémon Go, it only sees the raw data of the amount of exercise.
Many public health campaigns encouraging people to get off the couch and exercise for at least 30 minutes a day have fallen on deaf ears because the campaigns have been boring and their advertisers have looked unhappy.
However, the importance of exercise should not be underestimated.
Regular exercisers are less likely to develop cancer or depression.
Exercise helps in weight management, lowers blood pressure, prevents diabetes and brings a large number of other benefits.
The beauty of Pokémon Go is that it gets people out to do something they enjoy.
In this way, it achieves three basic health benefits – exercise, fresh air, and the sun and joy.
During the hunt, it is even possible to make new friends.
As usual, this phenomenon is frowned upon by spoilers of joy.
And yes, someone can walk through the door.
What's the big deal?
A breakthrough is made.
Because while smartphone apps like Fitbit may have tracked your activity in the past, they didn’t give you a reason to get going, like Pokémon Go does.
The novelty will disappear, and in time the use will decrease.
However, the success of the Pokémon will result in more games that combine apps and virtual reality with real-world activity, increasing the physical activity of the people who go hunting and improving their fitness and health.
