About 140,000 people suffer a heart attack each year in England, a quarter of whom have a heart attack or stroke.
Heart attacks and strokes are caused by fatty substances that build up in the walls of blood vessels and cause plaques.
If the plaque ruptures, it can cause a blood clot that prevents blood from entering the heart and causes a heart attack.
And if a blood clot breaks off, it can travel with the blood stream and block the flow of blood to the brain, resulting in a stroke.
The risk of a new attack is higher in people who have had a heart attack once.
The ticagrelor manufactured by the British company AstraZeneca and sold under the brand name Brilique reduces this risk by reducing the likelihood of plugs.
The draft NICE guidance published today recommends that ticagrelor be administered at a dose of 90 mg for the next 12 months, followed by a reduction to 60 mg, and that aspirin be administered twice daily for an additional three years.
Carole Longson, professor at the Center for the Evaluation of the Advancement of Clinical Practice (NICE), says: “While there are effective treatments available that effectively prevent the progression of the disease and the onset of symptoms, up to a quarter of people who have a heart attack will have another attack or stroke – often with fatal consequences.
The fear of relapse can have a very negative impact on a person’s quality of life.
We have found evidence that ticagrelor in combination with aspirin is effective in reducing the risk of new heart attacks and strokes in people who have already had a heart attack.
The recommendation of temporary use of ticagrelor increases treatment options for the thousands of people who benefit from it."
