It’s also not just a matter of hobbyists wanting to grab records, but it’s an emotional one: older vinyl record buyers are a little more likely to hide their feelings (56% vs. 53%) and enjoy being alone (69% vs. 66%).
But are the results of YouGov true?
If this blog was a televised newscast, the camera would follow me as I walked along bustling Soho Street, wearing a glamorous gray jacket. I would gesture briskly, bend my hand into a cup, and say something traditional like, “Let’s find out.”
So let's find out.
Although Soho has slowly lost its charm and roughness, as hotels, Eats, Prets and Paperchase chains have taken over before the holdings owned by private entrepreneurs, there are still a handful of specialty record stores left.
I would probably ask the cameraman to stop the camera for a moment as I get very close to the men visiting these shops and try to observe their age and temperament.
Stuart from Glasgow, 55, who I follow from Sister Ray (currently two young women, three middle-aged men) to Reckless Records (currently eight middle-aged men, one woman probably in her twenties) is on a meeting trip to London for the afternoon and spends his extra time exploring the shops.
I asked if he was a collector.
"I think I am," he says.
"I've got about 3,000 to 4,000 records."
These plates fill his living room walls, as you can see from the photo. (Stuart sent the picture to me by e-mail, I did not follow him home.)
The reason why he has acquired such a large number of albums and singles is partly due to his disposable income. He is now able to buy records that he could not afford when they first appeared, and again buy things that he had to sell when he was young and penniless.
"I get a lot of late '60s and early '70s stuff that came up when I was 11 or 12 and probably too young to get them," she says.
He agrees that those who buy vinyl records are more likely to be introverts who enjoy their own company, and adds, “I don’t smoke and I don’t drink much.
It's my vice."
Wez, 25, who works for Sister Ray, also believes that many of their customers fit the YouGov profile.
However, he has noticed a new kind of flow of people who have been affected by media hype. These people have heard of vinyl records coming back and now feel compelled to buy their old records back.
"Based on the conversations I had, people tended to give up their collections around 1998 or 1999.
Customers who sold their vinyl to buy CDs are now selling their CDs to buy their vinyl back,” he says.
This may explain the boom in vinyl-whiskers of a certain age.
What, though, about the supposed emotional significance of records?
In just a few seconds, in a movement like Phonica, you realize that they provide a comforting community for like-minded people.
According to Wez, some of the older customers are particularly upset about the contactless payment system.
The digital world may overwhelm some vinyl fans, for whom going back to their familiar record cases means permanence and reminds them of the happy days of their youth.
“I think it sometimes fills a gap or acquires material possessions for some kind of comfort,” says Wez.
"I see it as a collector myself, and I think so do many others.
It’s an easy way to get your mind off things.”
“We’re like social workers!” yells Wez’s co-worker from behind the pile of records.
An ICM opinion poll conducted in April revealed that nearly 50% of those who bought a vinyl album the previous month had not yet listened to the album.
The poll also found that 41% have a record player that they never use, and 7% of vinyl record buyers don’t have a record player of their own at all.
At this point in the newscast I would probably show a serious face while browsing through stacked bossa nova collections.
The re-emergence of vinyl records is also accompanied by the "pocalypse" phenomenon that Jonny, 42, a salesman for the Sounds of the Universe movement (currently three middle-aged men), has observed.
“A customer recently came into the store and said he doesn’t have a record player, but he wants to buy a Radiohead record so he can put it on his shelf,” Jonny says.
“It’s not a big deal, but there are customers.
For them, materiality is more important than music.
Some of our customers say they don’t have a record player yet.
They’re younger, not older, mostly teenagers who are just starting out.”
The customer base is much more varied in Foppi, where I will arrive next. The store has dedicated a whole layer to vinyl records.
Customers include couples in their 70s, tourists taking photos, teenage boys and middle-aged women.
The variety of customers delights, even if the atmosphere is not as relaxed as in the previous stores: instead of rocking jazz, the speakers are buzzing with the latest sex-filled synthesizer pop from Wild Beasts.
None of the customers seem particularly lonely, but it is difficult to detect the gnawing psychological trauma by standing next to someone for 30 seconds.
Elanora, 27, has been walking around Fopp for a few minutes and looking at different discounted albums.
He's more interested in watching than shopping.
He says his income is low, so collecting records is not possible for him.
"They cost a lot.
It is easy to listen to music on the computer or otherwise, but the fineness of the wine is ..." he sighs with delight and continues:
"I can't explain it, they're so unique."
My last stop is the store that is said to have inspired a new generation of vinyl fans: Urban Outfitters.
I see a bunch of teenage girls who think they're jumping around in denim shorts, but who instead gather around the Polaroid cameras for a moment, and I see a father and a daughter thinking about buying a Crosley turntable.
On the left is a staircase, the wall of which is filled with records by Adele, Jeff Buckley, Amy Winehouse and Fleetwood Mac: a mixture of contemporary music and classics, central records for any average collection.
No one looks at the wall, maybe because they are just a decorative element and some of them are so high that they can’t even be reached.
They are pure "art vinyl" interior.
But given that all the means to get attention on these boards may mean more money for the industry and sending a few customers on a search trip to Soho, there’s little to complain about.
It’s no surprise that the population group most likely to have more time and money than most is also the group that spends the most money on luxuries like vinyl records.
While my research shows that YouGov’s findings are true, at least in Soho’s record stores, they don’t rule out the large number of female collectors and vinyl fans that actually exist in both record stores and online forums.
These people are likely to be closely involved in school or work.
They certainly do not spend their Thursday mornings hanging out at the Berwick Street record stores, browsing through records and avoiding the 30-year-old who plays a TV presenter who looks frighteningly at and glances at unsuspecting middle-aged men.
