Central Command, or Centcom for short, is the headquarters of the United States Armed Forces in Tampa, Florida, responsible for military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
"Intelligence findings approved by Centcom's senior leadership tended to give a more positive picture of U.S. counter-terrorism efforts than the facts on the ground, and were invariably more positive than analyses by other units in the intelligence community," the report said.
“Centcom’s events are unacceptable – our soldiers suffer when high-level policymakers are presented with false analyses,” said Ken Calvert, the Republican representative from California.
“Mistakes by Centcom’s management reach the top of the organization.”
The 10-page report details ongoing problems in 2014 and 2015 with Central Command’s descriptions and analyses of American efforts to train Iraqi forces.
While the report does not contain conclusive evidence that the reports commissioned by the Obama administration were falsified, it does give analysts an impression that Centcom’s leaders were pressuring them to present a more optimistic view of the threat posed by ISIS.
“In the first half of 2015, many of the Central Command’s press releases, statements, and testimony to Congress were far more positive than the events actually were,” the report said.
For example, a Centcom official publicly stated that a major military offensive to recapture Mosul could take place as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq’s second-largest city, is still under ISIS control.
"After months of research, this is very clear," Kansas Republican Representative Mike Pompeo said in a statement.
"From mid-2014 to mid-2015, top U.S. military intelligence leaders manipulated intelligence findings to downplay the threat of ISIS in Iraq."
The group was set up by Republicans after they learned of analysts' suspicions that intelligence about ISIS had been manipulated.
