In the midst of the Olympic bustle, the trampoline brings zen
No matter the time or place, the Olympics are inevitable.
The events, races and struggles of Rio de Janeiro seem to be a constant, passionate message everywhere.
As if the Olympic flame itself was a flaming baton that passed from archer to swimmer, from swimmer to gymnast and from gymnast to triathlete.
You can’t turn on the TV, read the newspaper, or listen to your neighbor’s conversation in a coffee shop queue without hearing about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecky, or the fight between Michael Phelps and Chad le Clos.
And then there's a man named Logan Dooley.
Olympic first-timer Dooley charms with her smile and might well be the name on everyone’s lips that would be seen and heard at peak viewing and listening time, would be popular with sponsors, and would appear in good-humored TV commercials if she were a swimmer, gymnast, or even a fencer.
But Dooley, 28, from Lake Forest, California, competes for Olympic gold on a trampoline.
The Olympic flame does not illuminate all competitions equally.
Further away from the center, in part in the shade, are lesser-known sports such as air pistol shooting, archery, badminton, and taekwondo.
We will always have a breaststroke, and may the championship stay with us for a long time.
But if I may write a modest article about my own special favorites, I would like to draw attention to the understated charm of the trampoline.
Although the trampoline has been an Olympic sport since the 2000 Sydney Games, its visibility over the last 16 years has been so low that many of the people I interviewed did not even know it was an Olympic sport.
Ignorance can be regional.
The U.S. has participated in the Olympic trampoline, but has never won a medal or progressed to the finals until 2012.
On the men’s trampoline, the medals seem to go to the Chinese and Russians, and on the women’s side, the medals have been won by Canadians.
Dong Dong from China and Rosie MacLennan from Canada will defend the gold medals they won in London this year.
However, the trampoline has the charm of an underdog. Partly because to an uneducated ear it sounds more suitable for circus school than for the Olympics.
(I’m not an expert, just a fan.)
The species has its comic potential, which has been used in cartoons in the characters’ endless bounce scenes. But it also has the same dignity as gymnastics and swimming, i.e. the species that essentially combine on the trampoline.
The word trampoline comes from the Spanish word el trampol<0xC3><0xAD>n, which means "bounce board".
Ambitious champions jump on a huge trampoline, which catapults them to a height of almost 10 meters. Before landing on their feet, the jumpers must perform a series of acrobatic movements such as twists, folds and flips.
According to the official Olympic program, jumps are judged on performance, difficulty and "flight time".
In Rio, 32 athletes from 17 different countries compete for the trampoline gymnastics championship, 16 of them men and 16 women.
The most common direction for Olympic sports is straight ahead.
In the pursuit of gold, medal hopes must go further, faster, up and over, sometimes over the finish line, sometimes back and forth around the field.
In addition to the finish line or the starting wall, they also have another goal they pursue in televised reports, namely, world or Olympic records.
This determined pursuit is sublime, admirable, even fanatical – and it is enough even to bring the viewer to tears.
But I also find it a bit exhausting just to watch the games.
This trampoline offers a breather.
On the trampoline, the direction is upwards.
The goal is not to move forward.
The gymnast bounces up weightless like an astronaut, falls down and bounces back up effortlessly.
Of course, there’s also the competitive aspect, and it’s not easy either, but it doesn’t involve a frantic rush to the finish line or jumping far, it’s just a dreamy and fluid combination of time and gravity.
It’s as close to Zen as an Olympic competition can get.
