NBC will broadcast the finals as part of their afternoon broadcast, which will start at 2:00 p.m. local time on both days.
In the midst of the Olympic mania bring a peaceful and wonderful moment, which in the midst of the general hustle and bustle might go unnoticed.
And if awareness can only be raised by offering appealing male athletes to watch and objectifying them — as U.S. male gymnasts recently suggested, according to the Wall Street Journal — then Logan Dooley is just waiting for his panting new crowd of fans.
A whole generation protested in Ethiopia, a longtime ally of the United States
Violent Protests in Ethiopia
Government forces have violently dispersed demonstrations calling for political change across Ethiopia.
Witnesses said several protesters were shot dead in clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia falling apart?
For the past decade, it has been one of Africa’s most stable countries and a reliable Western ally with a rapidly growing economy.
In recent months, however, the country has been shaken by anti-government demonstrations, which are spreading to ever wider areas.
Last week alone, thousands of people took to the streets demanding radical political change.
According to human rights groups, the government’s response was merciless.
Witnesses said police shot and killed several unarmed protesters.
Video footage of the demonstrations, presumably at the end of last year or the beginning of this year, shows security forces using sticks to hit young people who have been forced to stand with their hands against a wall.
The UN’s chief human rights officer is now calling for a thorough investigation.
"Keeping the country united has always been difficult, and moving forward has been even more difficult," says Rashid Abdi, Research Director of the International Crisis Group of the Horn of Africa project.
Ethiopia is the second largest country in Africa after Nigeria, and has been supported by the West.
The US military and intelligence services are closely supporting the Ethiopians in the fight against terrorist threats throughout the region, particularly in Somalia, where few, if any, African countries receive this much help from the West.
Ethiopia’s economy is growing at a rapid pace.
Its infrastructure has radically improved, and there is even a new urban train in the capital, Addis Ababa.
The streets of the cities are usually calm, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia is still a long way from being a model country for democracy: human rights organisations have constantly reported on the repressive policies of the government, opposition in the country is very limited and dissidents are being quickly silenced.
Many people have been driven out of the country, imprisoned, killed or driven far into the wilderness.
But the situation may be changing.
"If a people is repressed and has no choice but to demonstrate, it will erupt," said Seyoum Teshome, a lecturer at the University of Central Ethiopia.
“All the young people are protesting.
A whole generation is protesting.”
There are many topics of dissatisfaction, ranging from land use to the government coalition’s stranglehold on power.
After last year's widely criticised elections, the ruling party and its allies took the last seat previously held by the opposition and, as a result, they now govern the whole of Parliament.
At the same time, tensions are escalating along the Eritrean border, where the escalating situation claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less defeated in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden People's Liberation Front, may seek to exploit the chaos and rearm themselves.
There are many reasons why the bitter mood that has been smoldering under the surface for years is erupting right now.
The first is obviously innocent: smartphones.
It is only in the last couple of years that Ethiopians have been able to communicate on social media, as cheaper smartphones have become commonplace and access to the internet has improved.
Even when the government repeatedly blocks access to Facebook and Twitter, especially during protests, many still access the internet via proxy servers that encrypt their whereabouts.
Many young Ethiopians reported that this was how they invited people to the demonstrations.
Another reason is the increase in solidarity between the two largest populations in Ethiopia, the Oromo and the Amhara.
Oromos and Amharas are not natural allies.
Amharic people from the predominantly Christian highlands of Ethiopia have long dominated the country’s politics and business and exploited the Oromo, many of whom are Muslim and live in the lowlands.
But this is also changing.
“The collaboration is deepening and we are getting under the same umbrella,” says oromo director Mulatu Gemechu.
The largest demonstrations have taken place in the Oromo and Amharic regions.
Many Amharic and Oromo people feel that Ethiopia is unjustly ruled by the Tigre tribe, which represents only about six percent of the population and yet controls the military, intelligence, trade and politics.
The third cause of the unrest is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Meles was the prime minister of Ethiopia for 17 years until he died of an unnamed illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius who could see around the corner.
According to analysts, he was particularly adept at spotting the first signs of discontent and using ambassadors to mediate between opponents.
“The current government lacks this essential instinct,” says conflict researcher Abdi.
Ethiopia’s new Prime Minister Hailemariam Desalegn stepped into Meles’s shoes from near obscurity.
Unlike Meles, who was from the Tigre region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam comes from the south.
Analysts say he has no confidence in the security forces run by the Tigre tribe.
Many fear that this will mean more bloodshed.
The last time similar riots took place in Ethiopia was in 2005, when thousands of people protested against the elections, which, according to analysts, were first botched and then stolen by the government.
In the post-election unrest, many protesters were killed, though fewer than in previous months, and the unrest ended relatively quickly.
Development experts have praised Ethiopia’s leaders for far-sighted infrastructure planning, such as the new urban train, and for the significant progress made in the fight against poverty.
But the internal resentment against the Ethiopian government has clearly not prevented it from intensifying.
And the resentment is taking on a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month in Gondar, Amharic, protesters attacked tiger-owned businesses, and hate speech against tigers is on the rise on social media.
Analysts say the protests are putting the United States and other Western allies in a difficult situation.
The U.S. government has used Ethiopia as a base for unmanned aerial vehicles monitoring neighboring Somalia, but the base has recently been closed, according to the U.S.
While the West clearly wants to support democracy, it also does not want its already unstable ally to collapse.
“It takes a lot of balance,” Abdi said.
