The Dreary Food of the Great Depression in the New Work: A Square Meal
In March 1933, shortly after becoming president, Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat down for lunch in his office at the White House.
President Roosevelt, known as a culinary artist, was fond of the luxurious dishes of Fifth Avenue restaurants, such as foie gras and Maryland turtle soup.
On that day, his menu was more modest: deviled eggs in tomato sauce, mashed potatoes, and plum pudding for dessert.
“It was an expression of culinary solidarity with the people who were suffering,” says Jane Ziegelman.
Her husband, Andrew Coe, added: “It was also a message to Americans about how they should eat.”
A couple living in Brooklyn Heights both work as food historians.
Coe’s latest book, Chop Suey, tells the story of Chinese cuisine in America, while Ziegelman’s latest book, 97 Orchard, tells the story of an apartment building in the Lower East Side through food.
Their new collaboration, A Square Meal, published Tuesday by Harper, chronicles the history of American food during the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The couple showed their own culinary solidarity by agreeing to meet with a journalist at Eisenberg's Sandwich Shop, a small and ordinary lunch bar near the Flatiron skyscraper and opened the same year as the Great Stock Market Crash of 1929.
Ziegelman, 54, ordered a cream cheese and olive sandwich and Coe, 57, ordered turkey, mashed potatoes and mixed vegetables.
When the reporter ordered a meatloaf, the couple said it fits very well into the discussion of eating during the Great Depression.
"The concerns were very popular," says Jane Ziegelman.
“People ate peanut butter, liver butter and bean jelly.
They were made of materials that were cheap and plentiful.
Imagine eating enough peanuts to eat the whole meal.”
Andrew Coe is grinning.
“It must have weighed like lead in the stomach,” he says.
Before the Great Depression, the American dining table, especially in the countryside, served on the buffet principle "eat as much as you want".
Women prepared food for farm workers, and freshly baked pies were served for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.
It was the Americans who had sent food to starving Europeans during World War I. A Square Meal is a chronicle of the ways in which the people survived when abundance was suddenly abandoned.
“This was the time when food became a central and distressing topic for Americans,” says Coe, explaining why he and his wife wanted to write about it.
Equally distressing was the new low-cost diet: according to Ziegelman, enigmatic dishes such as stews and casseroles became the staple food, and casseroles were said to be "a great way to make use of leftovers" because chefs could cover less attractive ingredients with cream sauce.
Fresh fruits were replaced with cheaper dried fruits.
Meat, which for years had been a staple of the American meal, became a sparingly used luxury.
We tried strange mixtures, where the most important thing was to meet the calorie and nutritional values, not so much the taste or even the common sense of the kitchen.
While doing research for a book that also includes recipes, Jane Ziegelman prepared baked onions stuffed with peanut butter, which were used as a shortage-time dish.
"It did not gain popularity at the dinner table," says Coe, where
Ziegelman adds: "It was unreal.
Peanut butter and oven onion don't go together at all.
This was characteristic of many household recipes."
Household experts, such as Louise Stanley, director of the Federal Household Administration from 1923 to 1943, guided the eating habits of citizens in an unprecedented and unique way.
They published recipes and articles in newspapers and magazines, and encouraged women to be accurate budget keepers and to meet the challenge of making tasty dishes from stuff like carrot-cream pages.
The book A Square Meal is a celebration of historical treats.
Particularly tasty are reports of the government's reactions to its hungry citizens, such as President Herbert Hoover's 'let me eat cake' attitude.
While publicly praising the simple food of his childhood on an Iowa farm, he himself ate, like the millionaire and sophisticated gentleman he had become.
"He liked continental European cuisine, such as fish and cucumber sauce," says Coe.
"He ate almost in a gold-plated dining room, wearing a tuxedo.
He was completely estranged from reality.”
President Roosevelt might have made the same mistake if his wife, Eleanor, had not encouraged him to lead by example with her belly.
