NASA climate model: Venus has been habitable
According to NASA’s new climate model, Venus may have been habitable.
NASA’s Goddard Institute for Space Studies (GISS) developed a model to study Venus’ past using the same tools and algorithms used by climate scientists.
The purpose of the model was to find out whether conditions on Venus were ever similar to those on Earth, even though Venus is hot and waterless on the surface and its atmosphere consists almost entirely of carbon dioxide.
According to the researchers, the slow rate of rotation of Venus is explained by its thick atmosphere.
However, the latest simulation suggests that Venus had a thin, Earth-like atmosphere, and yet it has been spinning slowly.
The model was also used to determine the early surface formation of Venus.
There were probably more dry areas on the planet than on Earth, but there may have been enough water and geographical variation to sustain life and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited from the sun, which was 30 percent dimmer.
"With GISS, Venus rotates slowly and has a day side toward the sun for almost two months at a time," said GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio.
This warms the surface and creates rain, which creates a thick layer of cloud, which acts like an umbrella and protects the surface from much of the sun’s heat.
As a result, average climate temperatures are even a few degrees lower than Earth’s current temperatures.
The model was used to create the story of Venus, which corresponds to earlier assumptions made by planetary scientists about its evolution.
While Venus may have been habitable, it has been exposed to excessive heat and ultraviolet light for billions of years.
Its oceans evaporated, and ultraviolet light burned the vaporized water.
With the escape of hydrogen into space, only a thick atmosphere of carbon dioxide and a lethal greenhouse effect remained —that is, Venus as it is today.
The researchers reported the results of a new Venus climate model in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
Patrick Roy resigns as Avalanche coach
Patrick Roy resigned on Thursday from his position as coach of the Colorado Avalanche and vice president of the team’s ice hockey operations, citing a lack of influence in the team’s decision-making.
Colorado Executive Vice President/CEO Joe Sakic confirmed the news and announced that the club would immediately start looking for a new coach.
“For the past three years, I have served as head coach of the Colorado Avalanche and vice president of the team’s hockey operations with vigor, passion and determination,” Roy said in a statement.
“Over the summer, I have thought long and hard about how I could improve the team, give it the necessary depth and raise it to a higher level.
To achieve this, the coach and the club’s vice president of ice hockey operations must be in complete alignment with the organization.
He must also have a say in decisions that affect team performance.
These conditions are not being met at the moment.”
Sakic, who hired Roy on 23 May 2013, thanked Roy for his investment in the team.
"Patrick told me about his decision today," Sakic says.
"We are grateful for all he has done for our organization and wish him all the best for the future."
Roy was awarded the Jack Adams Award as the league's best coach of the year for his first season as head coach of Avalanche from 2013 to 2014.
Under his leadership, the team scored 112 points and won the Central Division, but Colorado lost to Minnesota in the playoffs and has not reached the relegation period in the past two years.
The Avalanche scored 39-39-4 points in the 2015–16 season and was five points behind the Minnesota Wild for a second Wild Card position in the Western Conference.
Hall of Fame goaltender Roy won four Stanley Cups in his career – two for the Montreal Canadiens and two for the Avalanche.
North Sea oil workers start negotiations and stop strike
The main negotiators say that the wage strikes of the North Sea oil workers will be interrupted when all parties to the dispute participate in a new round of negotiations.
Strikes have been carried out against Wood Group, a provider of oilfield services, on drilling rigs in the North Sea owned by Royal Dutch Shell.
According to the joint statement of the parties, "Wood Group and the trade unions Unite and RMT confirm that they have agreed to restart the process in order to resolve the dispute".
Starting next week, we will be holding a number of all-day meetings over the next few weeks, where we will be dealing with issues from fresh perspectives.
The unions justified their recent action, which they said was the first in more than 25 years, in protest at possible wage cuts of up to 30%.
Due to negative market pressures, Wood Group will cut the tariffs of its contractors operating in the North Sea by about 9 per cent this year.
The reduction in the company’s tariffs follows a 10% reduction in the prices of contractors working on land in 20114.
According to the company, the additional cuts will give it the space it needs to cope with the downturn in the market.
Shell, in turn, has cut thousands of employees and announced plans to leave oil and gas operations in up to 10 countries in an effort to streamline operations following its mega-merger with the British energy company BG Group.
Lower crude oil prices and the economic situation resulting from the UK's decision in June to leave the European Union are putting pressure on energy companies.
Dave Anderson, a Scottish Member of Parliament, met with labour leaders earlier this week to discuss one of the biggest industrial conflicts in the North Sea for an entire generation.
According to him, the North Sea is vital for the region's economy.
“In the North Sea and across the country, we need an economy that benefits many, not just a few,” says Anderson.
Less than $1.4 billion is expected to be spent on new projects in the North Sea in 2016, compared to around $7 billion in the last five years.
Kepler measures the speed of rotation of stars in the Pleiadian Cluster
The Kepler Space Telescope’s latest mission has been to measure the rotational speed of stars, which has helped astronomers compile the most comprehensive list to date of the rotational speeds of stars in the Pleiades cluster.
With the new data, astronomers will be able to find out why stars in the same cluster rotate at different speeds and how rotation times are related to the planetary formation.
"We hope that by comparing the results to other star clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between the star's weight and age, and even the history of its solar system," said Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech's Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis in Pasadena.
The Pleiadian star cluster is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster were born around 125 million years ago, which means that they are just reaching their adult age.
They are now spinning faster than ever.
When the speed of rotation is at its peak, large amounts of stellar wind are released from growing stars.
These winds have a discriminating effect on stars as they pass through their magnetic fields.
As a star ages, its rotational speed begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotational speed of each star by tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable starspots (corresponding to sunspots).
The latest listed rotational velocity data suggests that larger stars rotate more slowly than smaller ones.
Rebull compares stars to dancers – bigger ones rotate slower than smaller ones.
"We see from the Pleiadian 'dance' that slow-rotating stars are typically larger, while the fastest-rotating stars are typically very light stars," says Rebull.
Because the Pleiadian star cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing the properties of stars in relation to their rotational speeds.
"The Pleiadian star cluster provides a support for theoretical models of the rotation of both younger and older stars," says Rebull.
We want to know more about how, when, and why the stars slow down their rotation and stop their “dance.”
Rebull and his colleagues present their latest analysis of Pleiadian rotational speeds in three new articles, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
